        F/A-18F Super Hornet
       </span>
       <span id="spanSection">
       </span>
      </div>
      <div id="SocialMediaLinks">
       <div class="social-icons">
        <a class="twitter" href="//twitter.com/share" onclick="return twitterShareClick()" target="_blank" title="Share on Twitter">

       <div id="cphMajorContent_dDescrp">
        <p>
         The Royal Australian Air Force F/A-18F Super Hornet fleet gives Australia an upgraded air combat capability for both air-to-air and air-to-ground mission until the full introduction into service of the
         <a href="http://www.airforce.gov.au/Technology/Future_Acquisitions/F-35A_Lightning_II/?RAAF-ZRnYQhJUh1u0e44uR32olOT1rt+Ym4K3">
          F-35 Lightning II
         </a>
        </p>
        <p>
         The twin seat F/A-18F Super Hornet can undertake air interception, air combat, close air support of ground troops and interdiction of enemy supply lines including shipping.
        </p>
        <p>
         The F/A-18F Super Hornets are based at Number 1 and Number 6 Squadrons at
         <a href="http://www.airforce.gov.au/RAAFBases/Queensland/RAAF-Base-Amberley/?RAAF-tixcqOo+FfSGpvktTn4V2/n/6DYHtD+g">
          RAAF Base Amberley
         </a>
         . They have recently participated in a range of exercises and operations including Exercise Pitch Black in the Northern Territory, Exercise Bersama Shield on the Malaysian Peninsula, and
         <a href="http://www.defence.gov.au/Operations/Okra/" target="_blank">
          Operation OKRA
         </a>
         in the Middle East.
        </p>
        <p>
         The F/A-18F Super Hornets are larger than the
         <a href="http://www.airforce.gov.au/Technology/Aircraft/Hornet/?RAAF-9SSttIt/E93/3lV4LgVxgxc0y4P09YW2">
          F/A-18A/B Hornets
         </a>
         . The aircraft's increased wing area allows them to carry more stores on their extra hardpoints.
        </p>
        <p>
         Air Forcehas 24 F/A-18F Super Hornets, which will ensurethat Australia's air combat capability edge is maintained until the full introduction into service of the planned F-35A Lightning II. The F/A-18F Super Hornet achieved
         <a href="http://www.airforce.gov.au/Capability/?RAAF-/kFUpPVag5Pqj5gUIp0CxtwJlFabWz0O">
          Final Operational Capability
         </a>
         inDecember 2012.
        </p>
        <p>
         <a href="http://www.defence.gov.au/AirCraftNoise/Environment/publicenvironmentreport.asp" target="_blank">
          Super Hornet flying operations and noise information at RAAF Base Amberley.
         </a>
        </p>
       </div>
       <div id="cphMajorContent_dWeapons">
        <table class="tableStyle2">
         <tbody>
          <tr>
           <th>
            Weapons
           </th>
           <td>

             </li>
             <li>
              AIM-9X Sidewinder missile
             </li>
             <li>
              Global Positioning System (GPS) - guided Joint Direct Attack Munition (JDAM)
             </li>
             <li>
              Air to Ground Missile (AGM)-84 Harpoon anti-ship missiles
             </li>
             <li>
              AGM-154C Joint Stand-off Weapon (JSOW)
             </li>
             <li>
              Joint Direct Attack Munitions (JDAM)
             </li>
             <li>
              Guided Bomb Unit (GBU)-54 Laser JDAM
             </li>
             <li>
              M61A2 20 mm nose-mounted cannon
             </li>
            </ul>
           </td>
          </tr>
         </tbody>
        </table>
        <p>
        </p>
       </div>
